@node "Overview" "DLG and UUCP: an overview"
 DLG and UUCP -- an Overview
 ===========================

Similarities can be drawn between DLG and UUCP's relationship in the same
way that they can be drawn between DLG and PDQMail.  In both cases, many of
the same components exist, but are named differently.


 DLG's Role
 ==========

In both cases, DLG exists mostly as an interface to the messages.  It
displays the messages for you to read them, and it accepts your input into
the message bases using exactly the same editor in both cases.  The only
real difference from DLG's point of view is that in the case of Fido, the
mail processing program handles all exporting and importing on its own. In
the case of UUCP, the master program suite (UUCP) stores its messages in a
format totally alien to DLG's. Thus, DLG contains components that handle the
final import and export stages.


 Front-End
 =========

The front-end for a mail system is that part of the system that talks to
other mailers.  FidoNet uses TrapDoor and other similar programs, and UUCP
has its front-end as well, UUCICO.  However, outgoing calls are handled
differently than incoming.

Your outgoing calls are made directly by UUCICO.  It in turn uses the UUCP
file exchange method to move files from your server to you.  It then fires
off UUXQT, which figures out what to do with the files you just received.

Incoming calls are handled using special user accounts called UUCP Clients.
You create this user account on your system from the sysop User editor. When
an external system calls, it "logs in" as a user. When it sends its name and
password, DLG will react accordingly.  It does this by looking at the UUCP
flag for that "user" account.  If it is set to CLIENT, DLG immediately
freezes the port and launches DLGConfig:Misc/UUCP.Batch. This program calls
GETTY, a UUCP program that grabs the serial port and facilitates file (mail)
transfers with the external UUCP site.  Once completed, the port is unfrozen
and the "user" is logged out.


 Importing
 =========

Importing refers to translating mail from an external system's format to one
DLG understands. With Fido, your main mail importer is PDQImp. For UUCP,
your mail importing is accomplished in two steps.  First, UUCP's RNews and
RMail programs (under control of UUXQT) import newsgroups and email
respectively and store them in UUCP's native format. This is useless to DLG,
so two DLG modules are used to bring in the mail -- UUCP2DLG (email) and
UNET2DLG (Newsgroups).

 Exporting
 =========

Exporting refers to translating mail from your system's format to one
understood by an external system. For FidoNet, PDQExp is the program that
accomplishes this.  For UUCP, as with importing, two steps are required.
First, a DLG module called DLGUUSend writes the message out to UUCP's
format, then calls SendMail to actually write the message to UUCP's storage
media. Then, for news, UUCP's BatchNews is run to bundle up your newsgroups
for transmission to remote systems. Email does not get batched.

 Maintenance
 ===========

Most mail systems require some sort of maintenance.  DLG's Fido software
more or less automates the tasks of triming message bases and other tasks
that must be done on a routine basis.  UUCP uses TrimNews for part of this,
and DLG's Renumber command accomplishes the rest (from the DLG side of the
house).

 Gluing it all Together
 ======================

All these programs doing all these different tasks require some bit of
control to work properly.  For FidoNet, PDQMail's resident process controls
everything for us, which is extremely convenient.  For UUCP, we have no such
central process, so we have to rely on some batch file magic to get things
done.
@endnode

@node "DLG-UUCP" "DLG UUCP Components"
 DLG UUCP Components
 ===================

DLG uses three programs to accomplish all of its UUCP mail processing.
Minimal changes are required in internal DLG configurations in order to get
UUCP to start working for you.


 UUCP2DLG
 ========

UUCP2DLG imports email from UUCP's format to a format understood by DLG. For
each "Mail box" it finds in the UUMail: directory, it reads in each message
and saves it in the user's private mail directory.  The user must exist on
your system for this to work.

Each user on your system has an email address that follows this format:

   First_Last@yourmachine.your_feed's_address.domain

(see the UUCP documentation herein for more on that address thing).

Each user may receive email whether or not that user has UUCP priveleges.


 UNET2DLG
 ========

UNet2DLG imports newsgroups from your UUNews: paths into the DLG message
bases that you have defined for it (see below).

At one time UNet2DLG required an assign for every newsgroup you wished to
import.  Under DLG 1.15 and later, this is not required.  All you need is
the UUNews: assign pointing to the UUMAIL:News/ directory.


 DLGUUSend
 =========

This program handles the writing of outgoing messages, handling both email
and newsgroup articles.  It is called automatically whenever you write a
UUCP email or newsgroup article.



 Configuration Issues
 ====================

   User Data
   =========

First of all, each user level that you wish to have write access for UUCP
email and newsgroups must have the UUCP WRITE flag set.  This is easy to
accomplish if you're just setting up, and is only slightly more difficult to
do if you've operated for a while and are just adding UUCP at this stage.
The best method is to define the lowest template you wish to have UUCP
access, then globally apply that template to all users, taking care to only
applying upgrading properties.  If the UUCP flag is all that changed, it is
the only thing that will be applied.


   Define message areas for newsgroups
   ===================================

For each message area that you wish to define as a UseNet newsgroup, you
must set the UUCP flag in the area's definition (Sysop menu, Define/Edit
Message areas), and also describe the newsgroup that the message base will
receive.  UNet2DLG scans each message base, and for each one that contains
the UUCP flag, it will look in UUNews:dir/dir/dir/dir for the messages
(where dir/dir/dir/dir corresponds to the newsgroup name dir.dir.dir.dir).


   Each User Defines UUCP signature
   ================================

While it is not required, remember that DLG appends a different signature
for UUCP email and newsgroups than it does for Echos, Alias, or Local
message bases.  You might set up a default login stack, or even better, a
bulletin AS a command stack, that will take them to the message menu and
invoke the EDIT SIGNATURE command.


   Configure UUCP
   =============

The most difficult part of this process is to configure UUCP itself. This
requires installing the UUCP system itself, setting up its configuration
files, and modifying your startups so that UUCP will run properly. Finally,
you need to set up some batch files so that you can glue it all together. An
entire section of this doc file is devoted to this issue.
@endnode

@node "UUCP_Install" "Installing UUCP"
 Installing UUCP
 ===============

Installing UUCP is not a simple matter of disolving the archives and making
it go.  There is a lot of tweaking and file-moving involved.  You will find
UUCP 1.17 in three files: one for binaries (required), one for manuals (not
required but REALLY REALLY recommended!), and one with source code (very
optional).  Once you dissolve these archives, you'll be able to move the
files around.  The contents of the archives break down thusly:

   Bin      -- Bin for Binary, where the programs are kept
   Lib      -- Lib for Library, where the configs are kept
   Mail     -- Where the mail lives is stored
   Man      -- Where the documentation is kept
   Pub      -- Associated with BMS -- you're on your own
   Spool    -- This is where files go during transfers.


 BIN

   This is where the actual UUCP programs are kept.  The UUCP: assign is
   made to this directory. You should not mix this with other executables.

 LIB

   This is where the UUCP configuration files are kept, as well as your
   list of newsgroups and other important files.  The assignment UULIB:
   points to this directory.

 MAIL

   This directory holds your mail.  Normally, email goes here until it is
   imported by DLG's UUCP2DLG.  The assignment UUMAIL: points to this
   directory.

   Inside of this directory is a directory called NEWS, and the UUNews:
   assignment points to this.  In this directory are nested all the
   directories for your UUCP newsgroups.

 MAN

   This directory holds the documentation for the UUCP binaries.  Once
   you've configured UUCP, typing MAN <command> will display the doc file
   for the command you've chosen.  The assignment UUMAN: points to this
   directory.

 SPOOL

   This directory is a "scratch" directory in which files are stored
   awaiting transfer to your feed, and where files are stored when
   received FROM your feed.  The assignment UUSPOOL: points here.  Inside
   this directory is another directory called BATCH.  Inside this
   directory would be files controlling what messages need to be batched
   for downlinks.


The following assignments, therefore, must be made once you've copied the
UUCP archives out.  For your convenience, this can be found in the S
directory of this archive as UUCP-Startup.  You can modify it and then add
the line

   execute s:uucp-startup

near the beginning of your dlg-startup file.


-8X---

   ; This is your UUCP setup file.

 Assign UUCP:      BBS:UUCP/bin         ; main UUCP executables
 Assign UUSpool:   BBS:UUCP/SPOOL       ; Input/output
 Assign UULib:     BBS:UUCP/LIB         ; UUCP's config dir
 Assign UUMail:    BBS:UUCP/Mail        ; where mail is kept
 Assign UUNews:    BBS:UUCP/Mail/News   ; where Newsgroups are kept
 Assign UUPub:     BBS:UUCP/Pub         ;
 Assign UUMan:     BBS:UUCP/Man         ; where I keep my man pages


 Assign GeTTY:     BBS:UUCP/LIB         ; Required for GeTTY
 Assign BMS:       BBS:UUCP/Lib/BMS     ;

 Path UUCP: ADD                         ; Always add to command path.

-8X---
@endnode

@node "Config_UUCP" "Configuring UUCP"
 Configuring UUCP
 ================

OK, once UUCP has been installed, you need to configure it.  The following
files should be found in this archive's UUCP/LIB directory:

   @{".SIGNATURE" link "_Signature" 0} -- a default signature file
   @{"ĀĀAliasĀĀĀ" link "_Alias" 0} -- email address remapping
   @{"ĀĀConfigĀĀ" link "_Config" 0} -- your main UUCP configuration file
   @{"ĀĀL.SysĀĀĀ" link "_L.Sys" 0} -- How to connect to your uplinks
   @{"NewsGroups" link "_Newsgroups" 0} -- A list of valid newsgroups
   @{"ĀĀĀseqĀĀĀĀ" link "_SEQ" 0} -- A counter file
   @{"ĀĀĀSysĀĀĀĀ" link "_Sys" 0} -- Newsgroup distribution

Note that the examples that we use are NOT comprehensive and you should read
the UUCP documentation for more specifics.
@endnode

@node "_Signature" ".SIGNATURE"
 .SIGNATURE

   If all works right, this file will never be used, but you never know.
   This contains a basic signature that could be appended to the end of a
   UseNet news article on its way out.  Mine looks thus:

-8X---

 /**
  **   The Techno-Mages' Guild BBS
  **   Home of DLG Pro BBOS
  **/

-8X---
@endnode

@node "_Alias" "Alias"
 Alias

   This file contains a list of aliases that can be used to remap mail.
   For example:

      sysop:Jeff_Grimmett

   This would remap mail for sysop@elric.maximumaccess.com to me.

      sysop:Jeff_Grimmett,Holly_Sullivan

   This would remap mail for sysop to myself and Holly.

      dlg_sysop: /Jeff_Grimmett,/Holly_Sullivan,
                 Mike_Moon@not.connected.net

   This would remap mail for dlg_sysop to myself, Holly, and Mike Moon (if
   he actually had an email address :-)

   Complex pattern matching is possible.  Use MAN ALIAS to get the full
   rundown on this.  You can leave this file out until you need it.
@endnode

@node "_Config" "Config"
 UULIB:Config

   This is the heart of your UUCP system.  This minimum config will
   probably get you by.  As you understand UUCP better and better, you can
   make it more elaborate:

-8X---

 ; Your machine's name.  YOU come up with this name, and inform your feed
 ; of the name to use.

 NodeName       elric

 ; Most used for single-user systems, but used in other areas too.
 ; One is underscored, the other is not.

 UserName       Jeff_Grimmett
 RealName       Jeff Grimmett

 ; Your BBS name, or anything else that fits

 Organization   The Techno-Mages' Guild * DLG Pro HQ

 ; Used to read news via dmail and for reading man files.

 Filter         C:More
 RFilter        C:More

 ; your feed's root name.  This you get from your feed's site
 ; administrator.

 DomainName     .maximumaccess.com

 ; Your time zone. EST for Eastern Standard Time, or example, or for
 ; Pacific Daylight Time:

 TimeZone       PDT

 ; the machine that your machine talks to for your main feed. This also
 ; you get from your feed's site administrator.

 DefaultNode    baluga

 ; used to initialize your modem.  The \d\d portion causes a delay,
 ; required for the more complex high-speed modems, which are pretty
 ; common these days.

 ModemInit      ATZ0\r\d\d

 ; This makes UUXQT not run automatically -- we'll run it from a batch
 ; file later, don't worry.

 UUXQT dummy

-8X---
@endnode

@node "_L.Sys" "L.Sys"
 UUCP:L.SYS

   L.Sys defines how your system connects to others when calling out.
   Initially, you only need one entry:

   This will get most people by.

-8X---

 #   This is a comment.

 baluga Any SER: 28800 2782421 ogin: uelric sword: test\r

-8X---

 ^      ^   ^    ^     ^       ^
 |      |   |    |     |       |
 |      |   |    |     |       +-- A sequence of expect - response
 |      |   |    |     |           strings. See below.
 |      |   |    |     |
 |      |   |    |     +-- Your provider's phone number
 |      |   |    |
 |      |   |    +-- The baud rate you are using
 |      |   |
 |      |   +-- The device to "talk" to.
 |      |
 |      +-- Scheduling info.  Leave as is until you get things working.
 |
 +-- The name of the server you will connect to.


   The expect-send string is a series of expected strings, and the
   response we will send back when we see them.  In the above example,
   UUCICO waits until it sees "ogin:" and then it sends "uelric", which is
   my UUCP account on my ISP.  Then we wait for "sword:" and we send our
   password ("test" in the above case -- hey, it's a fake, all right? :).

   This sequence of strings can go on indefinately, in theory.

   You'll note that the "Login" and "Password" prompts are attenuated in
   the above example.  This is on purpose.  The reason for this is that
   the case of the login prompt might change -- "Login" as opposed to
   "login", and UUCICO is case-sensitive.  So, we lop off that first part.
@endnode

@node "_Newsgroups" "NewsGroups"
 UULIB:NewsGroups

   This is a list of all your valid newsgroups, and (optionally) how many
   days' worth of news to keep on your system.  Mine looks something like
   this:

 --8x-----

 alt.appalachian 1
 alt.archery 1
 alt.consumers.free-stuff 1
 alt.fairs.renaissance 1
 alt.genealogy 1
 alt.history.living 1
 alt.humor.best-of-usenet 1
 alt.sewing 1
 alt.sys.amiga.demos 1
 alt.sys.amiga.blitz 1
 alt.sys.amiga.thor 1
 alt.sys.amiga.uucp 1
 alt.sys.amiga.uucp.patches 1
 bit.listserv.i-amiga 1
 comp.sys.amiga.advocacy 1
 comp.sys.amiga.announce 1
 comp.sys.amiga.applications 1
 comp.sys.amiga.audio 1
 comp.sys.amiga.cd32 1
 comp.sys.amiga.datacomm 1
 comp.sys.amiga.emulations 1
 comp.sys.amiga.games 1
 comp.sys.amiga.graphics 1
 comp.sys.amiga.hardware 1
 comp.sys.amiga.introduction 1
 comp.sys.amiga.marketplace 1
 comp.sys.amiga.misc 1
 comp.sys.amiga.multimedia 1
 comp.sys.amiga.networking 1
 comp.sys.amiga.programmer 1
 comp.sys.amiga.tech 1
 comp.sys.amiga.unix 1
 comp.sys.amiga.uucp 1
 misc.consumers.frugal-living 1
 rec.crafts.textiles.misc 1
 rec.crafts.textiles.quilting 1
 rec.crafts.textiles.sewing 1
 rec.music.dementia 1
 rec.org.sca 1
 rec.sport.archery 1
 soc.genealogy.methods 1
 soc.genealogy.misc 1
 soc.genealogy.surnames 1
 soc.history.living 1

 --8x-----

   One newsgroup is listed per line, with (optionally) a number following
   it.  If no number is specified, 7 (a week's worth of news) is assumed.
@endnode

@node "_SEQ" "seq"
 UULIB:SEQ

   Unless you got UUCP 1.16 before you got 1.17, this is undocumented. SEQ
   is a sequence number, and is used in generating a unique identification
   number for every message posted from your system.

   It is a simple text file.  To set it up, type the following in a shell:

      Echo >UULIB:SEQ "1"

   That's it!
@endnode

@node "_Sys" "Sys"
 UULIB:SYS

   This file contains information about what newsgroups are routed to what
   servers.  Most systems will have a grand total of one line:

--8x---

   baluga:narwhal:news:*

--8x---


   The above line can be translated as: "Send all newsgroups (the "*") to
   baluga, also known as narwhal, also known as news".

   Our system actually connects to "baluga", so all news bundled will be
   sent to it.  However, our news server is named "narwhal" so we have to
   ensure that we accept any news that comes from it.  Finally, our news
   server is also known as "news" (or more completely,
   news.maximumaccess.com) so we have to ensure that our outgoing news
   articles have its name in them.

   In essense, then, the above line indicates that baluga, narwhal, and
   news are the same entity.

   The basic format of a SYS line is, then,

      <server>:<newgroups>

   The newsgroups can be either explicitly indicated, or wildcarded.
   Consider this:

--8x---

   baluga:narwhal:news:*
   vir:comp.sys.amiga.*
   gkar:alt.*
   londo:-*.amiga.*

--8x---

   This scenario has me getting my primary feed from baluga/narwhal/news,
   and supplying a downlink to vir, who is an Amiga fanatic, gkar, who's
   interested only in the alt newsgroups, and londo, who doesn't care much
   for the Amiga.
@endnode

@node "Batch" "UUCP Batch Files"
 Putting it all together

Now that we've configured our software, we're ready to start putting it all
together.  I have found that a maximum of 4 batch files are really needed,
along with some CronTab entries.

 @{"UUCPPoll.batch" link "_UUCPPoll.batch" 0} -- polling your feed
 @{"UUCPCall.batch" link "_UUCPCall.batch" 0} -- calling your feed
 @{"UUCPToss.batch" link "_UUCPToss.batch" 0} -- tossing UUCP mail
 @{"ĀĀĀĀUUCP.batch" link "_UUCP.batch" 0} -- handling incoming calls
 @{"ĀĀĀĀĀĀĀCronTab" link "_CronTab" 0} -- Some sample CronTab entries
@endnode

@node "_UUCPPoll.batch" "UUCPPoll.batch"
 DLGConfig:Batch/UUCPPoll.batch

   As with any mailing system, you need to either poll out to collect your
   mail, or your feed needs to call you.  Generally, you call your feed.

   UUCICO looks for a poll file that indicates who to call each time it
   calls out.  To create this file, we use a simple batch file.

   The polling script accepts one argument, the name of a server (as
   specified in @{"L.Sys" link "_L.Sys" 0}) to call.  In my case, it is "baluga".

      Execute DLGConfig:Batch/UUCPPoll.batch baluga

--8x--

 .key site/a
 .bra "["
 .ket "]"

 ; this parses the name of the server to call, and sets [] as our bracket
 ; characters.

 ; first, we only do this if a poll file does not exist.

 if not exists uuspool:C.[site].poll
    echo >uuspool:c.[site].poll
    endif

--8x--

   This script, called with the parameter I stated above, would create
   UUSPOOL:baluga.poll.


   This script should be executed on a regular basis to ensure that you
   get your mail reliably.  You can accomplish this with a @{"crontab" link "_CronTab" 0} entry.
   I call out 4 times daily, but nothing is stopping you from calling
   every hour.
@endnode

@node "_UUCPCall.batch" "UUCPCall.batch"
 DLGConfig:Batch/UUCPCall.batch

   This batch file actually handles the calling out to collect our mail.
   It is a bit complex, so I've commented it liberally.

   Syntax:

      Execute DLGConfig:Batch/UUCPCall.batch <site name>

   Where the site name is one specified in @{"L.Sys" link "_L.Sys" 0}.

   In my case:

      Execute DLGConfig:Batch/UUCPCall.batch <baluga>

   You should execute this batch file on a regular basis, at least as many
   times as you create poll files.  See the example @{"crontab" link "_CronTab" 0} for an easy
   way to do this.

--8x---

 .key site/a
 .bra "["
 .ket "]"

 ; ^-- Parse site name, then change bracket characters to [].

 ; don't load down the CPU

 ChangeTaskPri -4

 ; we only do this if the @{"pollĀfile" link "_UUCPPoll.batch" 0} exists for our site.

 if exists UUSpool:C.[site].poll

 ; batch file magic: this will prevent the batch file from being run again
 ; before we're done.

    DLG:GetResource -n UUCP

 ; Now we grab the port when it becomes available.

    DLG:GetPort -p TR0 -k "UUCP" -r "UUCICO session - polling [site]"

 ; we increase the failure code to 11 so that UUCICO will not cause the
 ; batch file to exit if it doesn't connect.

    failat 11

 ; This is for a 7wire (high-speed) connect.  We redirect it into con: so
 ; that we can watch it in operation.

    UUCP:UUCICO -A -X6 -s[site] -7 -n7 >con:

 ; Now, if we didn't connect, UUCICO will generate a "warning" (code 10)
 ; which will tell us that it was not successful.

    if not warn

 ; if we connected OK, we import our mail.

       run >Con: execute @{"DLGConfig:batch/UUCPToss.batch" link "_UUCPToss.batch" 0}

 ; if we DIDN'T connect OK (warning), we need to free the UUCP resource so
 ; that we can call again later on.

    Else
       FreeResource -n UUCP
       EndIf

 ; all done now, so let's release the port.

    DLG:FreePort -p TR0 -k "UUCP"

    EndIf

--8x---

   The basic sequence of events is this:

      First, we down the priority of the batch file so that it won't bog
      down other processes running.  Then, we check to see if a @{"pollĀfile" link "_UUCPPoll.batch" 0}
      for our site exists.  If not, we skip everything else.  If it does,
      we continue.

      The next step is a bit of batch file magic made possible through
      DLG. The GetResource program will allow you to define your own
      resources that you can lock using the resource manager, TPTRM. As
      we're using it here, it will attempt to lock the resource and not
      continue until the resource is made available, thus we queue up
      subsequent events.  If this is a bother, use the -i option and it
      will fail if the resource is locked, thus breaking the script.

      Next, we grab the port of our choice.  You can use a port that has
      TrapDoor loaded on it if you wish.  The standard DLG batch files
      allow us to take down TrapDoor if we lock the port it's on, and
      bring it back up when the port is released.  The we we are invoking
      it here, it will wait if there is a user online, then snatch the
      port when the user logs off.

      Next, we change the failat level for this batch file.  To understand
      this, you need to undertand how batch files work.  If a program
      returns a code 10 or higher, AmigaDOS batch files will by default
      "break".  A code 10 from a program, or higher, is considered a hard
      failure.  However, UUCICO, the following program, returns a code 10
      if it simply gets a busy signal.  We don't want to stop the batch
      file because of that.  So, we up the failure level to 11.  Now, if
      UUCICO gets a busy signal, it will return 10 but it will only be
      considered a WARNING.  We can work with that.

      The next step, as you gathered, is to call out using UUCICO. In the
      above example, it is redirected to CON:, thus giving us a window
      where we can watch the action.

      Once UUCICO is done, we do one of two things.  If UUCICO made a
      connection, we will execute @{"UUCPToss.batch" link "_UUCPToss.batch" 0} and process our mail.  If
      not, we must free the resource UUCP, otherwise the next attempt will
      not go through either.  Otherwise, it is freed in the UUCPToss.batch
      file.

      Finally, we release the port that we locked earlier.  This allows
      the port to be used for normal BBS activity once again.
@endnode

@node "_UUCPToss.batch" "DLGConfig:batch/UUCPToss.batch"
 DLGConfig:Batch/UUCPToss.batch

   This batch file is fairly straightforward.  In fact, all this stuff
   _could_ be incorporated into UUCPCall.batch if you wanted, but keeping
   it seperate makes things simpler.

--8x---

 ; we don't want to bog down the computer

 ChangeTaskPri -6

 ; set higher if needed, especially if unexplained crashes occur

 stack 80000

 ; this program sorts out the email from the newsgroups and puts them
 ; in the right places.

 uuxqt

 ; import email into DLG user mailboxes

 DLG:UUCP2DLG

 ; import newsgroups

 DLG:UNet2DLG

 ; optional: if you have NewsLink and don't mind the extra time it takes,
 ; it is an excellent idea.

 ; DLG:/DLGUtils/NewsLink

 ; Trim down your newsgroups

 UUCP:TrimNews

 ; All done, so let's release the UUCP resource that was locked in the call
 ; batch file.

 FreeResource -n UUCP

--8x---

As you can see, there isn't much to it.  One item that is also optional is
TrimNews.  A lot of people prefer to run it once daily to minimize drag on
the system.  This would be accomplished with an entry in your crontab.

Note that we free the UUCP resource at the end of this batch file.  With the
UUCP resource locked by the call batch file, and freed here, we ensure that
we don't have two invocations of this batch file running at the same time.
It is important that this not happen, if for no other reason that mere
sanity. :-)
@endnode

@node "_UUCP.batch" "DLGConfig:Batch/UUCP.batch"
 UUCP.batch

   This batch file is called by DLG:Door when a "user" logs in that has
   the UUCP CLIENT flag set in "his" account.

   It is very simple:

--8x---

 .key port/a,device/a,unit/a

 failat 100
 path uucp: add
 UUCICO -getty -DEVICE <device> -UNIT <unit>

 ; really important! DLG:Door "freezes" the port before calling this batch
 ; file.  In order for it to be used again, we have to unfreeze it using
 ; TCont.

 tcont -p <port>

--8x---

   It first parses the port, device, and unit of the device (ie, "TR0",
   "serial.device", "0"), supplied by DLG:Door.  Then, it sets the fail
   code WAY up high, adds UUCP: to the command path (just in case), and
   calls UUCICO in host mode.

   The last step is most crucial.  DLG:Door "Freezes" the serial port,
   basically suspending the BBS on that port for the duration. This allows
   8-bit clean I/O over the port without the handler attempting to remap
   or filter anything.

   The reverse of TFreeze, and program that freezes the port, is TCont,
   which allows normal handler activity to continue.

   Optionally, you could add

      GetResource -n UUCP
      Execute >CON: @{"DLGConfig:Batch/UUCPToss.batch" link "_UUCPToss.batch" 0}

   at the end of this batch file, and it would automatically process any
   mail from your downlink.
@endnode

@node "_CronTab" "crontab"
 Sample CronTab Entries

   As with Fido mail, you will probably wish to automate and schedule your
   UUCP mail.  Here are a few examples from my crontab file.

--8x---

# min hour dom mon dow

#once a year, reset UULIB:SEQ to 1.

0 17 6 4 * echo >UULIB:SEQ "1*N"

# Create a poll file 5 times daily

1 4,8,12,16,22 * * * run execute dlgconfig:batch/UUCPPoll.Batch baluga

# Attempt to get mail every 15 minutes

1,15,30,45 * * * * run execute dlgconfig:batch/UUCPCall.Batch baluga


--8x---
@endnode

@node "Alternative Methods" "Alternatives"
 Alternative Methods of Getting Internet Mail

UUCP is fairly primitive technology these days, and you might find it hard
to locate an ISP that offers a UUCP feed for reasonable fees.  If that is
the case, what are the alternatives?  There are many, but we will only
discuss them in the most general of terms for now (a later version of this
document may be more explicit).

UUCICO is a direct serial transport mechanism, meaning it has no
intermediaries between it and the machine on the other end.  However, it is
not limited to just the serial port.  If you have a TCP/IP connect already,
you can use it to transport mail without dialing out.  You can also use it
to dial out to one ISP, telnet to another, and then get the mail from THERE.
I know of at least one sysop in Europe that is feeding from a news server in
the U.S. this way.  Just remember that you can use as many expect-send pairs
as needed in your L.Sys file's string.

Another method, one gaining much popularity, is SMTP (Simple Mail Transfer
Protocol) and NNTP (Network News Transfer Protocol).  These work with TCP/IP
stacks like AmiTCP, NetBSD, and Miami.  To use these with DLG, you will need
an SMTP-to-UUCP filter to change the mail's format to one that DLG can
handle.  Future versions of DLG will be able to parse these directly.

Another method is to skip DLG's involvement altogether. A lot of software
these days works directly through the shell and SMTP/NNTP mail.  AmiELM for
mail, AmiTIN for news.  Scripts and environmental variables can be used to
make these work online in DLG's multiuser environment.  I consider these
kludges at best, but, to be honest, so's DLG's UUCP environment, something
that I WILL improve in future versions.

   (for anyone that is curious, I insist on using DLG's native modules for
    UUCP, so I will be well motivated to improve them! :-)
@endnode

@node "Gateways" "Gateway Software"
 FidoNet to UUCP Gateways

As Skip Watson once stated (in less agreeable terms (now I'm in for it!)),
FidoNet BBSs with UUCP accounts tend to like to show off a little bit and
offer a gateway service, usually for fidonet to internet email, but often to
gate newsgroups into FidoNet or vice-versa.

The situation in this regard is bleak.

At the moment, I have found one fully working gateway package, and that one
is faulty as the dickens.

 MonaLisa

   Nice concept, but it has two failings:

   First, it's all GUI -- no fast an speedy method of setting up a lot of
   newsgroups at once.

   Second, its author seems to have dissapeared, and, since it requires
   registration to work all the way, it is useless without registration.


 NetGate

   One of our beta testers uses it and has much good to say about it.
   Since it requires SMTP and I use UUCP -- no comment.


 AmiGate

   This one came recommended to me, but it has a number of bugs which I
   have worked out in batch files and kludges  These are included without
   comment in a directory called AmiGate.  Feel free to ask me what the
   heck I was thinking when I put them together. :-)



 Using UUCP as a FidoNet transport layer

   This is often referred to as a "gateway" but really isn't.  I have
   implemented this on my system and it appears to work quite well. I have
   included a collection of batch and config files showing how it can be
   used in a directory called "FidoXport".  It also includes a clever Rexx
   script which *is* required to make it work, along with a guide file
   that makes things a little clearer :-)


Due to the rather rotten nature of Amiga UUCP gateway software, I will be
integrating UUCP import modules into DLGMail -- which is also a good idea in
its own right :-)
@endnode

